		<div id="process" class="[ full-space ] [ flow ] ">
			<h2 class="alpha">The Process</h2>
			<p>Working through a cryptic crossword clue usually involves a few short steps. Let’s take a look at these steps using an example clue:</p>
			<p class="delta">Table of mixed up letters (7)</p>
			<ol>
				<li>Identify the <em>type</em> of clue based on certain words or wording being used. This is usually in the form of a single word or phrase which indicates what you need to do with the clue to get the answer. → <q>mixed up</q></li>
				<li>Based on the type of clue, identify the part of the clue that needs to be manipulated to get the answer from. → <q>letters</q></li>
				<li>Lastly, find the part of the clue that contains the definition of the answer. Oftentimes, identifying this part is obvious because clues tend to avoid superfluous words, so there are only three <q>parts</q> to the clue’s phrase/sentence in the first place. → <q>table</q></li>
			</ol>
			<p>Putting this all together, the phrase <q>mixed up</q> tells us that this is an <strong>anagram</strong> type of clue, and we need to unscramble the word <q>letters</q> to get a new word that means <q>table</q>:</p>
			<p class="delta">TRESTLE</p>
		</div>

		<div id="anagrams" class="[ full-space ] [ flow ] ">
			<h2 class="alpha">Anagrams</h2>
			<div class="anagram-demo gamma center monospace" id="anagram-demo" style="display: none;">
				<span style="--order: 19;">T</span><span style="--order: 7;">O</span><span style="--order: 4;">M</span><span style="--order: 2;">&nbsp;</span><span style="--order: 16;">M</span><span style="--order: 3;">A</span><span style="--order: 8;">R</span><span style="--order: 11;">V</span><span style="--order: 12;">O</span><span style="--order: 10;" class="after">&nbsp;</span><span style="--order: 6;">L</span><span style="--order: 17;">O</span><span style="--order: 5;">&nbsp;</span><span style="--order: 18;">R</span><span style="--order: 1;">I</span><span style="--order: 9;">D</span><span style="--order: 14;">D</span><span style="--order: 13;">L</span><span style="--order: 15;">E</span>
			</div>
			<p>An anagram is a word or phrase that is formed by rearranging the letters of a different word or phrase. With these types of clues, you’ll normally find that part of the clue’s wording tells you to transform a word or phrase to form the <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anagram">anagram</a> to be solved, e.g. <q>becomes</q>, <q>turns into</q>, or <q>wildly</q>.</p>
			<p>For example, given the following clue:</p>
			<p class="center"><strong style="display: inline-block; background-color: oklch(from currentColor l c h / 90%); padding-inline: 0.5em">The mutating corona virus seems like a flesh-eater (11)</strong></p>
			<p>We know that we’re looking for an 11-letter word, and the word <q>mutating</q> is a pretty good indicator that this is an anagram-type clue. In this case, the synonym of the answer is <q>flesh-eater</q>, and if we rearrange <q>corona virus</q>, we get:</p>
			<p class="center"><strong style="display: inline-block; background-color: oklch(from currentColor l c h / 90%); padding-inline: 0.5em">CARNIVOROUS</strong></p>
